tic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Gwilym","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Gwilim","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Gwillym","meanings":["equivalent of <b>William</b> , in use since the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Gwilym ap Dafydd was born about 1357, in Breconshire, Wales. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Gwilym ap Dafydd."},"et":{"about 1357–":"umbes 1357–Surnud","1353–Male":"1353–Surnud","1379–Male":"1379–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1357–Female":"1357–Surnud","1357":"1357","1379":"1379","1353":"1353","about 1357":"umbes 1357","about 1379":"umbes 1379","1380":"1380","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","Gelligaer, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gelligaer, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1357–":"noin 1357–Kuollut","1353–Male":"1353–Kuollut","1379–Male":"1379–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1357–Female":"1357–Kuollut","1357":"1357"